Melting Pot’s Business Case: 
ICS Poker Night

Introduction/Background
	One of the main goals of the ICS Student Council is to raise awareness for the major through campus-wide events. In addition, the Student Council also hosts events for ICS students and faculty that allow students to socialize while raising money for future events. In this case, the quarterly ICS Poker Night event will be held during week 8 of winter quarter 2011. The ICS Student Council believes that the school of computer science and its student council will greatly benefit from hosting the event again. 

Business Objective
	The Student Council aims to bring the ICS  student community closer through social events, networking opportunities, and various academic functions. The Poker Night event falls into the first two categories, and it allows students to socialize with each other, faculty, and various sponsors through a night of competitive Texas Hold ‘Em Poker. By selling tickets for the event, the ICS Council aims to gain more funding for potential future events. Not only does this event allow students, faculty and others to socialize, it also helps fund future projects and events that are of interest to the school of Computer Science.

Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement
	The ICS Student Council currently has a variety of options for its marketing strategies. They range from mailing lists and Facebook events to paper fliers and marketing personnel. Since the basic architecture for planning and executing such an event already exists, we strive to make plan the event more efficiently and produce greater results. We plan to use all available resources at our disposal in order to plan this event. The ICS Student Council currently holds this event on a quarterly basis.  The recurring event indicates the need for future event planning.  Additionally, there are other events and the possibility of new events for ICS which need planning.  Doing a successful job planning this event will likely lead to future projects with our team.  Repeat work will allow us to make improvements to an already successful ICS Poker Night.  It is also likely that the ICS Student Council will want to use a planning group they are familiar with, which gives Melting Pot an advantage for future event planning.

Critical Assumptions and Constraints
In order to meet all requirements, the event must be planned by the date scheduled by the ICS council and cannot go over the budget distributed by the ICS council.  The budget must be finalized by the end of Week 3, and the marketing must be ready to be sent out by the end of Week 4.  The event must pay for itself and generate excess revenue which is to be used to plan and execute future events. Any of the special requests made by the ICS council must also be considered.  An assumption is that the limit on the number of people will be for how many people can participate in games (i.e. no more people allowed than number to make a complete game).  Another assumption is that the number of games will be limited to an even number to better improve tournament timing and equality (no one person in the finals of the tournament would have played more required games than the others). In addition, one must consider a limit on the number of attendees.  Because the event is planned to take place in DBH 6011, an 80 person limit is reasonable, and goes along with what the ICS Student Council has set in the past.

Analysis of Options and Recommendation
	There are a few options for addressing this opportunity:
Do Nothing. The ICS Student Council managed to organize this event without any external help during the previous execution of the event.
Provide specialized help to the ICS Student Council to attract more sponsors, students, faculty and alumni to participate in the event but leave the planning and execution of the event up to the ICS Council.
Provide full support and become the acting planning committee for the ICS Student Council and help them plan the entire event.
	Based on our discussions with the stakeholders, we believe that option (c.) is the best option.

Preliminary Project Requirements
The primary requirement is that the project must be offered Thursday, February 24 (week 8) with all logistics planned. In addition, all food, drinks and equipment must also be provided and accounted for in order for the requirements to be fully met.  Invitations to ICS students, faculty, and sponsors must also be sent out at least two weeks beforehand with appropriate time, location and information (i.e. duration, cost of attendance if any, availability food and drink are provided) listed. There should an open and direct channel of communication between the PM of Melting Pot and a representative from the ICS Student Council in order for the team to be updated on necessary information relating to the event.


Budget Estimates and Financial Analysis
This project is designed to be very flexible in terms of its implementation but very rigid in terms of its budget. The budget, which has not yet been finalized, will be decided by ICS council and is based on the funding provided by various IT company sponsors and its money in the treasury. A breakdown of costs for refreshments, equipment, prizes, and promotions will be provided as reference for faculty, student council, and event sponsors. Approximately 80-90% of the money received from ticket sales will be used as the budget for the event thus resulting in a 10% profit which will be reserved for planning future events.
Based on similar past events, the following budget estimates can be made and they will form the basis of our project until we receive further updates from the ICS Student council regarding this matter:
	Food and beverages:		$200
	Marketing:			$50
	Prizes:				$200-$1000 (varying based on ticket sales)

Schedule Estimate
The event must occur on Thursday, February 24 (week 8). This means that the event planning must be finalized by Thursday, February 3 (week 5). The marketing materials must be delivered by Thursday, February 10 and the logistics finalized on the same day (week 6). The budget must be delivered by Sunday, January 23 (end of week 3).

Potential Risks
	The foremost risk associated with this project is a lack of interest to attend by faculty and sponsors. If there are no attendees, the ICS Council will lose money by funding the event, the sponsors will most likely not be satisfied with the end result, and the event might be reconsidered for being held quarterly. However, through efficient marketing, the event will most likely be successful.
	Another risk related to the event is that none, or few IT companies will be willing to fund the event. If this is the case, there will be limited funding for refreshments, equipment, prizes, etc., which will in turn lessen the satisfaction of the attendees. In the worst case, this might lead to asking the ICS Council for more funding. 
	Lastly, due to poor time management or lack of sponsors, we -- the project management team -- may have to postpone or even terminate the project. However, this would not be acceptable, as the ICS Student Council is expecting us to plan the event by a certain date and execute it within a certain time frame. 
	These risks tie together under one main risk: investing time, personnel and money in the project without its successful execution and realizing the full benefits that may result such a successful execution.
